Exploratory data analysis (EDA) is usually the first step in analyzing data because you want to know what information the dataset contains. In this lab, we introduce basic R functions for EDA in both quantitative and visual approaches. We will also learn some useful functions for data manipulation, which is often necessary in data analysis.

Exploratory Data Analysis by Numbers

Basic Summary Statistics

Before you begin, always:

  • set the working directory,
  • create a new R script (unless you are continuing a previous project), and
  • save the R script.

Lets first load the iris dataset. This is a very well-known dataset in data mining courses. This dataset is built into R.

It only produces the location statistics for continuous variables and counts for categorical variables. If you want summary statistics only for the numeric variables, you can use the Filter() function. (This is desirable if your data includes categorical variables with many levels whose counts might otherwise clutter your output.)

summary(Filter(is.numeric, iris))
##   Sepal.Length    Sepal.Width     Petal.Length    Petal.Width   
##  Min.   :4.300   Min.   :2.000   Min.   :1.000   Min.   :0.100

##  Median :5.800   Median :3.000   Median :4.350   Median :1.300

You can use basic R functions to calculate additional statistics.

# standard deviation
sd(iris$Sepal.Length)
## [1] 0.8280661
# quantiles
quantile(iris$Sepal.Length)
##   0%  25%  50%  75% 100% 
##  4.3  5.1  5.8  6.4  7.9

Use apply() to calculate a particular statistic for multiple variables at the same time.

apply(iris[, 1:4], 2, sd) # "2" means by "column"
## Sepal.Length  Sepal.Width Petal.Length  Petal.Width 
##    0.8280661    0.4358663    1.7652982    0.7622377

Summary by Groups

Use the aggregate() function to find summary statistics by group. The dot represents all variables except for Species, meaning your finding the mean for all other variables by Species.

# group mean
aggregate(. ~ Species, iris, mean)
##      Species Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width
## 1     setosa        5.006       3.428        1.462       0.246
## 2 versicolor        5.936       2.770        4.260       1.326
## 3  virginica        6.588       2.974        5.552       2.026
# group standard deviation
aggregate(. ~ Species, iris, sd)
##      Species Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width
## 1     setosa    0.3524897   0.3790644    0.1736640   0.1053856
## 2 versicolor    0.5161711   0.3137983    0.4699110   0.1977527
## 3  virginica    0.6358796   0.3224966    0.5518947   0.2746501

What if there are multiple factor variables?

Lets first artificially create a new column that categorizes Sepal.Length by quantile.

# Use the "cut" function for categorization based on quantiles
Cat.SepalLength <- cut(iris$Sepal.Length, breaks = quantile(iris$Sepal.Length), include.lowest = TRUE)
# Add the created categorical variable to the data
iris1 <- iris
iris1$Sepal.Length.Cat <- Cat.SepalLength

Mean by two groups

aggregate(. ~ Species + Sepal.Length.Cat, iris1, mean)

Exploratory Data Analysis by Visualization

Basic R Plots

Histogram

A histogram is the easiest way to show how numerical variables are distributed.

Produce a single histogram

hist(iris$Sepal.Length, col = "green", breaks = 20)

You may change col= and breaks= to change the color and the number of bars in your chart.

Density Plot - Fitted Curve for Histogram

A density plot is a nonparametric fitting.

plot(density(iris$Sepal.Length))

Combine the histogram and density plot

You can make the plot more elegant by applying different options. For example, adding a title, adjusting the axis range, renaming the axis label, and so on

You can also add curves on top of an existing plot by using the lines() or abline() function.

hist(iris$Sepal.Length, probability = TRUE, col = "green", breaks = 20, main = "Histogram and Density of Sepal Length", xlim = c(3, 9), xlab = "Sepal Length")
lines(density(iris$Sepal.Length), col = "red", lwd = 2)

# Add a vertical line that indicates the average of SepalLength
abline(v = mean(iris$Sepal.Length), col = "blue", lty = 2, lwd = 1.5)

Bar Chart

A bar chart is produced by using a single vector of data points, which is often a vector of summary statistics. Therefore, you need to preprocess your data and get summary statistics before drawing the bar chart.

# bar chart for count of records by job category
CustomerData <- read.csv("CustomerData.csv")
countjob <- aggregate(CustomerData$CustomerID, by = list(CustomerData$JobCategory), 
                      FUN = length)
names(countjob) <- c("Job", "CountOfCustomers")
barplot(height = countjob$CountOfCustomers, names.arg = countjob$Job, 
        xlab = "Job", ylab = "Count")

You can also create a bar chart for the average of the numeric variables (though there are better visualizations for showing measures of location).

# bar chart for average of the 4 quantitative variables in the iris data
aveg <- apply(iris[, 1:4], 2, mean)
barplot(aveg, ylab = "Average")

Pie Chart

A pie chart is commonly used visualize the proportion of some whole made up by each level of some factor. It is similar to a bar chart. You must use a vector of single data points to produce a pie chart.

pie(table(CustomerData$JobCategory), col = rainbow(7))

Box Plot

A box plot can only be drawn for continuous variables.

# box plot of Sepal.Length
boxplot(iris$Sepal.Length)

Box Plot for Multiple Variables in One Figure

boxplot(iris[, 1:4], notch = TRUE, col = c("red", "blue", "yellow", "gray"))

Box Plot by Group

boxplot(iris[, 1] ~ iris[, 5], notch = TRUE, ylab = "Sepal Length", col = "blue")

Scatter Plot

Simple Scatter Plot of Two Numerical Variables

plot(iris$Sepal.Length ~ iris$Sepal.Width, xlab = "Width", ylab = "Length",
     main = "Sepal")

You might also want to add a different color for each species.

par(xpd = TRUE)
plot(iris$Sepal.Length ~ iris$Sepal.Width, ylab = "Sepal Length", xlab = "Sepal Width",
     col = ifelse(iris$Species == "setosa","blue",
                  ifelse(iris$Species == "versicolor","red","green")))
legend("topleft", inset = c(0, -0.2), legend = c("setosa", "versicolor", "virginica"),
       col = c("blue", "red", "green"), pch = 1, cex = 0.9)

#### Scatter Plot Matrix

plot(iris[, 1:4])

You could also use the pairs() function to create the same chart.

plot(iris[, 1:4])

Parallel Coordinates Plot

library(MASS)
parcoord(iris[, 1:4], col = iris$Species)

Correlation Matrix with Heatmap

Try creating a correlation matrix with a heatmap for all numeric variables in CustomerData.

library(gplots)
## 
## Attaching package: 'gplots'
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     lowess
colfunc <- colorRampPalette(c("green", "white", "red"))
heatmap.2(cor(Filter(is.numeric, CustomerData)), Rowv = FALSE, 
          Colv = FALSE, dendrogram = "none", lwid=c(0.1,4), lhei=c(0.1,4), col = colfunc(15),
          cellnote = round(cor(Filter(is.numeric, CustomerData)), 2),
          notecol = "black", key = FALSE, trace = 'none')

Note the blank rows and columns. This is because those variables contain missing data. To calculate correlations only for non-missing values, add use = complete.obs to your cor() function.

library(gplots)
colfunc <- colorRampPalette(c("green", "white", "red"))
heatmap.2(cor(Filter(is.numeric, CustomerData), use = "complete.obs"), Rowv = FALSE, 
          Colv = FALSE, dendrogram = "none", lwid=c(0.1,4), lhei=c(0.1,4), 
          col = colfunc(15), 
          cellnote = round(cor(Filter(is.numeric, CustomerData), use = "complete.obs"),2),
          notecol = "black", key = FALSE, trace = 'none')

R Graphic Options

You may display multiple plots in one window (one figure).

# set arrangement of multiple plots
par(mfrow = c(2, 2)) # mfrow() and mfcol() serve the same purpose
# set margins
par(mar = c(4.5, 4.2, 3, 1.5))
hist(iris$Sepal.Length, xlab = "Sepal Length", cex.lab = 1.5)
hist(iris$Sepal.Width, xlab = "Sepal Width", col = "red")
plot(iris$Sepal.Width ~ iris$Sepal.Length, xlab = "Length", ylab = "Width", 
     main = "Sepal", pch = 17)
boxplot(iris[, 1:4], notch = TRUE, col = c("red", "blue", "yellow", "gray"))

There are many more options you can use to make your plot look nice. You can learn more about some of them here or you can google specifically what your hoping to do.

Details about figure margins can be found here.

Youll see that HouseholdSize, NumberPets, NumberCats, NumberDogs, NumberBirds, and HomeOwner are missing data.

For the sake of this exercise, well delete records that are missing data for HouseholdSize, NumberPets, and NumberCats.

CustomerData <- CustomerData[!(is.na(CustomerData$HouseholdSize) |
                                 is.na(CustomerData$NumberPets) |
                                 is.na(CustomerData$NumberCats)), ]

Imputing Values

We will now impute the median for NumberDogs, NumberBirds, and HomeOwner.

CustomerData$NumberDogs[is.na(CustomerData$NumberDogs)] <- median(CustomerData$NumberDogs,
                                                                  na.rm = TRUE)
CustomerData$NumberBirds[is.na(CustomerData$NumberBirds)] <- 
  median(CustomerData$NumberBirds, na.rm = TRUE)
CustomerData$HomeOwner[is.na(CustomerData$HomeOwner)] <- median(CustomerData$HomeOwner,
                                                                  na.rm = TRUE)

Categorical Variables

You may have noticed in the summary that somme of the categorical variables have blank values or error values, both of which indicate missing data. It would be wise to consider either omitting these or imputing some other factor. You would omit the same way you would with a numerical variable. To impute, try the following:

# view the different levels of the categorical variable *TownSize*
levels(CustomerData$TownSize) 
## [1] "#NULL!" "1"      "2"      "3"      "4"      "5"
# add a new level called 'N/A'
levels(CustomerData$TownSize) <- c(levels(CustomerData$TownSize), 'N/A')
levels(CustomerData$TownSize)
## [1] "#NULL!" "1"      "2"      "3"      "4"      "5"      "N/A"
# replace '#NULL!' values with 'N/A'
CustomerData$TownSize[CustomerData$TownSize == '#NULL!'] <- 'N/A'
summary(CustomerData$TownSize)
## #NULL!      1      2      3      4      5    N/A 
##      0   1427   1045    903    856    746      2

You can do the same for blank values.

levels(CustomerData$Gender)
## [1] ""       "Female" "Male"
levels(CustomerData$Gender) <- c(levels(CustomerData$Gender), 'N/A')
levels(CustomerData$Gender)
## [1] ""       "Female" "Male"   "N/A"
CustomerData$Gender[CustomerData$Gender == ''] <- 'N/A'
summary(CustomerData$Gender)
##        Female   Male    N/A 
##      0   2486   2460     33

Creating Dummy Variables

Well now create dummy variables for the first few categorical variables (factors) in CustomerData.

dummies <- model.matrix(~ 0 + TownSize + Gender, 
                        data = CustomerData)
dummies <- as.data.frame(dummies)

# look at the names of the dummy variables
t(t(names(dummies)))
##       [,1]            
##  [1,] "TownSize#NULL!"

##  [4,] "TownSize3"

Summary

After this lab, youre expected to know basic EDA techniques in R. EDA is crucial for any data analysis project.

Things to Remember

  • How to obtain basic summary statistics
  • Summary statistics by group
  • Pivot tables
  • Use of [ ] for subsetting and indexing
  • Basic R graphics
  • How to delete rows and impute values to account for missing data
  • How to create binary dummy variables
